            <section id="surveyor-opinion" class="content-section space-y-6">
                <h2 class="text-3xl font-semibold text-amber-700 border-b-2 border-amber-200 pb-2">üßê Surveyor's Opinion on Purchase</h2>
                <div class="bg-orange-50 p-6 rounded-lg shadow">
                    <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed">The property at 11 Russell Street, Stafford, presents as a characteristically challenging but potentially rewarding purchase, typical of its 1900-1929 era. Its solid brick construction and traditional layout are appealing, but as with many properties of this age, it comes with a significant list of defects and required maintenance, many of which are rated as Condition Rating 3 (serious/urgent) or Condition Rating 2 (requiring attention).</p>
                    <h4 class="text-md font-semibold text-amber-600 mt-4 mb-2">Key Considerations for Purchase:</h4>
                    <ol class="list-decimal list-inside space-y-1 text-sm">
                        <li><strong>Immediate and Significant Costs:</strong> External render, roof structure (damp timbers, woodworm, torn felt, incomplete party wall, vermin), electrical system (likely full rewire), and outbuilding (subsidence) require urgent attention. The surveyor's report (p.11-13) notes indicative costs such as: Remove render ¬£4,000 <span class="cost-source">(Surveyor Estimate)</span>, Roofer inspection ¬£300 <span class="cost-source">(Surveyor Estimate)</span>, Repair torn felt ¬£600 <span class="cost-source">(Surveyor Estimate)</span>, Complete party wall ¬£1,500 <span class="cost-source">(Surveyor Estimate)</span>, EICR ¬£250 <span class="cost-source">(Surveyor Estimate)</span>.</li>
                        <li><strong>Damp Issues:</strong> Penetrating damp linked to external render defects. Specialist investigation crucial.</li>
                        <li><strong>Ongoing Maintenance:</strong> Higher than modern counterparts (slate roof, timber fascias).</li>
                        <li><strong>Safety Concerns:</strong> Electrical system, incomplete loft party wall, no cellar stair handrail, need for modern smoke/CO alarms, non-safety glazing in lounge doors.</li>
                        <li><strong>Financial Prudence:</strong> Budget a minimum of ¬£15,000 - ¬£25,000 <span class="cost-source">(Gemini Synthesized Estimate based on surveyor and Gemini figures)</span> for the most urgent works, potentially significantly more post-specialist investigations.</li>
                        <li><strong>Potential vs. Risk:</strong> Offers potential but significant risk and financial uncertainty due to extent of defects.</li>
                    </ol>
                    <h4 class="text-md font-semibold text-amber-600 mt-4 mb-2">Recommendation:</h4>
                    <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed">This property is <strong>only suitable for a purchaser who has significant funds readily available</strong> for immediate and ongoing repairs, and who is experienced with, or prepared for, managing extensive renovation work on an older property.</p>
                    <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed mt-2"><strong>Before committing to purchase, it is absolutely essential to:</strong> Obtain detailed written quotations for ALL CR3 and significant CR2 items, factor these costs (plus 20-30% contingency) into your budget, and satisfy all legal enquiries. If budget is tight or a quick, trouble-free move is desired, this property is likely unsuitable. The EPC D rating also indicates desirable long-term energy efficiency improvements.</p>
                </div>
            </section>

